    "answer_id" : 958074,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Don't mess with the library path!  Eclipse builds it itself!</p>\n\n<p>Instead, go into the library settings for your projects and, for each jar/etc that requires a native library, expand it in the <em>Libraries</em> tab.  In the tree view there, each library has items for source/javadoc and native library locations.</p>\n\n<p>Specifically: select <code>Project</code>, right click -> <em>Properties</em> / <em>Java Build Path</em> / <em>Libraries</em> tab, select a .jar, expand it, select <em>Native library location</em>, click <em>Edit</em>, folder chooser dialog will appear)</p>\n\n<p>Messing with the library path on the command line should be your last ditch effort, because you might break something that is already properly set by eclipse.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/zeFNt.png\" alt=\"Native library location\"></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7257,
      "reputation" : 30730,
      "user_id" : 12541,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/Yk2vr.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Scott Stanchfield",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12541/scott-stanchfield"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1244235043,
    "creation_date" : 1244235043,
    "answer_id" : 958076,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>For a given application launch, you can do it as jim says.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to set it for the entire workspace, you can also set it under</p>\n\n<pre><code>Window-&gt;\n  Preferences-&gt;\n    Java-&gt;\n      Installed JREs\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Each JRE has a \"Default VM arguments\" (which I believe are completely ignored if any VM args are set for a run configuration.)</p>\n\n<p>You could even set up different JRE/JDKs with different parameters and have some projects use one, other projects use another.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 349008,
      "reputation" : 134,
      "user_id" : 684033,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b1b91aab6c1df616dd94e1fcd168b141?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "sonaht",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/684033/sonaht"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 8,
    "last_activity_date" : 1303702980,
    "last_edit_date" : 1303702980,
    "creation_date" : 1303642216,
    "answer_id" : 5770117,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can simply add <code>-Djava.library.path=yourPath</code> to the <code>eclipse.ini</code>. </p>\n"
  }, {
