    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1398087895,
    "creation_date" : 1398087895,
    "answer_id" : 23198715,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>the easiest way would to use the eclipse IDE itself. Go to the menu and set build path. Make it point to the JAVA JDK and JRE file path in your directory. afterwards you can check the build path where compiled files are going to be set. in the bin folder by default though. The best thing would be to allow eclipse to handle itself the build path and only  to edit it similar to the solution that is given above</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3531905,
      "reputation" : 997,
      "user_id" : 2951193,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f5b4feb78676b7e9e6e029214394ab10?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "marc",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2951193/marc"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1426084689,
    "creation_date" : 1426084689,
    "answer_id" : 28989530,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here is another fix:</p>\n\n<p>My build system (Gradle) added a required native library (dll) to the Eclipse build path (Right Click on Project -> Properties -> Java Build Path -> Libraries). Telling the build system not to add the native dll library to the Eclipse classpath solved the problem.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5131079,
      "reputation" : 10482,
      "user_id" : 4111295,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 67,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/V9WSf.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "alexventuraio",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4111295/alexventuraio"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1427770413,
    "creation_date" : 1427770413,
    "answer_id" : 29359807,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I'm using Mac OS X Yosemite and Netbeans 8.02, I got the same error and the simple solution I have found is like above, this is useful when you need to include native library in the project. So do the next for Netbeans:</p>\n\n<pre><code>1.- Right click on the Project\n2.- Properties\n3.- Click on RUN\n4.- VM Options: java -Djava.library.path=\"your_path\"\n5.- for example in my case: java -Djava.library.path=&lt;/Users/Lexynux/NetBeansProjects/NAO/libs&gt;\n6.- Ok\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>I hope it could be useful for someone.\nThe link where I found the solution is here:\n<a href=\"http://examples.javacodegeeks.com/java-basics/java-library-path-what-is-it-and-how-to-use/\" rel=\"nofollow\">java.library.path – What is it and how to use</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6555363,
      "reputation" : 425,
      "user_id" : 5068212,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/-spx1_nH4hxk/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAVw/44UyKgxUk4w/s256-rj/photo.jpg",
      "display_name" : "della raharjo",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5068212/della-raharjo"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1589210143,
    "last_edit_date" : 1589210143,
    "creation_date" : 1516249499,
    "answer_id" : 48313836,
    "question_id" : 957700,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can add vm argument in your Eclipse.</p>\n\n<p>Example :</p>\n\n<pre><code>-Djava.ext.dirs=cots_lib\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>where <code>cots_lib</code> is your external folder library.</p>\n"
  } ],
